<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-146-198  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 146 198.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InTech  Jan 1989 v36 n1 p27(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Factory automation: is it right for your company? (Reader's Forum)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Armbrust, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Although many manufacturers are unsure about automation, mostwould benefit from some degree of automation.andP;  Chief amongmanufacturers' concerns are employee reaction to automation,selecting the right consultant and selecting the right technology.andO;One mistaken assumption often made by manufacturers is thatautomation will allow them to cut back on the size of theirworkforce.andP;  While this is seldom true, other payoffs makeautomation cost-efficient, including improved productionefficiency, improved labor efficiency, and increased qualitycontrol.andP;  Company-wide integration is another benefit if factorycomputers are linked to front-office computers.andP;  This allowsfunctions such as sales to be tied to production.andP;  Automationshould begin with a small pilot project and then move on to largerapplications.andP;  Consultants should fit a system to the company'smethod of production, rather than vice versa.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Factory ManagementAutomationManufacturersPersonnel ManagementHardware SelectionEfficiency.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>